Key finding: RecordConverter completely bypasses XStream's SecurityMapper type permission system by calling Class.forName() directly instead of mapper.realClass(). This affects three code locations: classForName() at line 222, findClass() at line 228-232, and the unmarshal() child element processing at line 163-167. All other XStream converters properly use mapper.realClass() which flows through SecurityMapper's permission check.

The static initializer forName/newInstance calls (lines 58-61) are false positives using hardcoded strings for Java compatibility. The componentValue() invoke() call (line 203) is a false positive used in the marshal (not unmarshal) path with non-XML-controlled method names. SecurityMapper itself is correctly implemented (manual review) - the security gap is in how RecordConverter bypasses it.
